qas.question: What was Strasbourg called in 12 BC?
What was the Roman camp destroyed by?
Who was leading the Romans at Argentoratum?
After what year was the Legio VIII Augusta permanently stationed in Argentoratum?
How many times was Argentoratum rebuilt during the first and fifth centuries AD?
In what year did the Romans establish a military outpost?
In what year were the Legio XIV Gemina Roman Legions first stationed in Argentoratum?
In what year was the Legio XXI Rapax Roman Legions first stationed in Argentoratum?
In what year was Nero made emperor?
For how many years was Argentorate made the toponym of the Gaulish settlement?

context: The Romans under <a2_0>Nero Claudius Drusus<a2_0/> established a military outpost belonging to the Germania Superior Roman province at Strasbourg's current location, and named it Argentoratum. (Hence the town is commonly called Argentina in medieval Latin.) The name "<a0_0>Argentoratum<a0_0/>" was first mentioned in <b5_0>12 BC<b5_0/> and the city celebrated its 2,000th birthday in 1988. "Argentorate" as the toponym of the Gaulish settlement preceded it before being Latinized, but it is not known by how long. The Roman camp was destroyed by <a1_0>fire<a1_0/> and rebuilt <a4_0>six times<a4_0/> between the first and the fifth centuries AD: in <b8_0>70<b8_0/>, <b7_0>97<b7_0/>, 235, <b6_0><b9_0>355<b9_0/><b6_0/>, in the last quarter of the fourth century, and in the early years of the fifth century. It was under Trajan and after the fire of 97 that Argentoratum received its most extended and fortified shape. From the <a3_0>year 90<a3_0/> on, the Legio VIII Augusta was permanently stationed in the Roman camp of Argentoratum. It then included a cavalry section and covered an area of approximately 20 hectares. Other Roman legions temporarily stationed in Argentoratum were the Legio XIV Gemina and the Legio XXI Rapax, the latter during the reign of Nero.
